.TH N_RESET_IND 7 "@PACKAGE_DATE@" "@PACKAGE@-@VERSION@" "Network Provider Interface (NPI)"
.SH NAME
.B N_RESET_IND, N_reset_ind_t
\- reset indication
.SH DESCRIPTION
This network-provider-originated primitive indicates to the NS user that the
network connection has been reset.
.SH SYNOPSIS
The format of the message is one
.B M_PROTO
message block, and its structure is as follows:
.sp
.nf
\fC\s-1\
typedef struct {
    ulong PRIM_type;            /* always N_RESET_IND */
    ulong RESET_orig;           /* reset originator */
    ulong RESET_reason;         /* reason for reset */
} N_reset_ind_t;
\fR\s+1
.fi
.SH PARAMETERS
.TP
.I PRIM_type
Indicates the primitive type.

.TP
.I RESET_orig
This parameter indicates the source of the reset.
.RS

.TP
.B N_USER
The primitive originated at the remove NS user.

.TP
.B N_PROVIDER
The primitive originated at the remote NS provider.

.TP
.B N_UNSPECIFIED
The origination of the primitive is unknown or unspecified.
.RE

.TP
.I RESET_reasonr
Gives information indicating the cause of the reset.
.SH STATE
This primitive is valid in the
.B NS_DATA_XFER state.
.SH "NEW STATE"
The new state is
.BR NS_WRES_RIND .
.SH HISTORY
.PP
The Network Provider Interface first appeared in SVR 4.
